# PR Lifecycle Automation

When an agent is asked to submit PR work, babysit CI, or prepare a branch for merge, use the repo-local lifecycle helpers before inventing a custom flow.

## Primary Entry Points

- Use `.cursor/skills/ship-and-babysit/SKILL.md` to move a branch from local work to merge-ready.
- Use `.cursor/skills/merge-and-clean/SKILL.md` only after the user explicitly approves merge and cleanup.
- Use `pnpm pr:stack` for Graphite submission.
- Use `pnpm pr:validate` for local focused regression coverage.

## Approval Boundaries

- Never auto-merge without explicit user confirmation in the current conversation.
- Never auto-clean branches or worktrees without explicit user confirmation in the current conversation.
- Stop and ask when review feedback or conflicts are ambiguous.

## CI Source Of Truth

- Prefer `gh pr checks` for current status.
- Prefer `gh run view --log-failed` for the actual GitHub Actions failure cause.
- Keep CI fixes scoped to one failure cause per commit whenever practical.

## Submission Rules

- Prefer `pnpm pr:stack` over raw `gt submit` so Graphite tracking, mergeability preflight, and PR metadata refresh stay consistent.
- If the working tree is dirty, route through the scoped effort submit workflow instead of hand-rolling Graphite commands.

## Validation Rules

- Always run `pnpm pr:validate` after substantive PR-fix changes.
- Trust the printed validation profile instead of guessing the relevant package commands.
- Escalate to the wasm matrix only when `pnpm pr:validate` selects it based on changed paths.

## Browser Smoke

- Only run a `browser-use` smoke pass when changed files touch `apps/docs`, `packages/react`, or another clearly UI-facing surface.
- Keep browser checks brief and regression-focused; do not turn them into exploratory QA unless the user asks.

